Governments, hospitals and schools have come to see the value in buying locally grown food.
No Silicon Valley tech company worth its stock price would dare to design a cafeteria without local food.
For the first few weeks, farmers scrambled to find other ways to sell their crops.
Some turned to online sales or tapped a renewed interest in community-supported agriculture, or C.S.A.s, in which farmers sell subscriptions for boxes of produce.
Others delivered food to restaurants that had turned into pop-up grocers, or doubled down on the farmersâ€™ markets that remained open.